{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532448"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14675"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14675"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.72,0.15,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7368"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14675"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5583"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a widespread itchy rash that developed seven hours after having an outpatient CT scan with intravenous contrast. She has no fever or other systemic symptoms. She has had six months of intermittent bouts of diarrhoea and constipation, and takes no regular medications. She later admitted that she completed a course of oral cephalexin five days prior for a sore throat and fatigue, though her symptoms resolved before her investigation today. She has no known previous allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a symmetrical, erythematous, maculopapular rash across her trunk and limbs. There is no mucosal involvement, no blistering, and no target lesions. The rash blanches on pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Viral exanthem","Radiocontrast media hypersensitivity","Epstein-Barr virus infection","Contact dermatitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic delayed hypersensitivity reaction to radiocontrast media. The timing of onset (seven hours after exposure), pattern of rash (maculopapular), and absence of systemic symptoms are characteristic features. Though this is relatively rare (4%), it should be considered in otherwise well patients for up to 1 week post-administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed contrast media hypersensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is thought to be a T-cell mediated (type IV) hypersensitivity reaction that typically presents as a maculopapular exanthem. The mechanism involves T-cell recognition of contrast media or its metabolites bound to proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, fatigue, lymphadenopathy, and pharyngitis before the development of a rash, which can be triggered by amoxycillin administration, not cephalexin. While this patient had recent sore throat and fatigue, the clear temporal relationship to contrast administration and type of antibiotic makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe mucocutaneous reaction that typically presents with fever, malaise, and painful target lesions with mucosal involvement. The absence of these features and the temporal relationship to contrast administration make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral exanthem\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in the context of viral prodromal symptoms such as fever, malaise, or upper respiratory symptoms. The timing to contrast administration makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically localised to areas of direct skin contact with an allergen and presents with erythema, vesicles, and intense pruritus. The widespread distribution and timing after intravenous contrast make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement includes documenting the reaction, symptomatic treatment with antihistamines and topical steroids if needed, and identifying safe alternative contrast agents for future use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delayed hypersensitivity reactions to radiocontrast media typically present 6 hours to 1 week after exposure with maculopapular rash."],"references":["Radiocontrast Media Hypersensitivity. Australia Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy. 2022. Available at: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp/drug-allergy/radiocontrast-media","Hsieh C, Wu SC, Kosik RO, Huang YC, Chan WP. Pharmacological Prevention of Hypersensitivity Reactions Caused by Iodinated Contrast Media: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. Diagnostics (Basel). 2022 Jul 9;12(7):1673. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9320945/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14675"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92238","lin